                    <emph>multiple Scriptural sources and his </emph>
                    <emph>inconsistent </emph>
                    <emph>handling of the source-texts make it </emph>
                    <emph>hard</emph>
                    <emph>to account for the nature and development of Hobbes’s treatment of the Bible.</emph>
                    <emph> </emph>
                    <emph>That is why, w</emph>
                    <emph>ith the notable exception of the pioneering study by Harold W. Jones (</emph>
                    <emph>Jones, </emph>
                    <emph>1984), even modern scholarship has rarely dared to venture in a methodical examination of Hobbes’s </emph>
                    <emph>B</emph>
                    <emph>iblical knowledge and exegesis (Pacchi </emph>
                    <emph>et al.</emph>
                    <emph>, 198</emph>
                    <emph>8</emph>
                    <emph>; Somos, 2015).</emph>
